The example is the wrong case.  Unless you are using MyISAM tables (hint: 90%+ of the time you shouldn't), there's rarely a situation to LOCK TABLES as described.<p>Using transactions would make more sense:<p><pre><code>  try {
    mysql_query("START TRANSACTION");
    // ... do lots of queries here
    mysql_query("COMMIT");
  } catch(Exception $e) {
    mysql_query("ROLLBACK");
  }</code></pre>
